<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-29T13:48:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-29T13:48:00-05:00" n="22" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 715.1715/39</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Curtis</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-29T13:00:00-05:48">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 29, 1918, 1 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Supplementing my July 24, 1 p.m.<note n="1" xml:id="d22fn1">Not
                                    printed.</note> Both the Honduran Government and the Nicaraguan
                                Government profess anxiety to sign an arbitration treaty, but both
                                appear to desire especially to place the onus of failure on the
                                other. The Nicaraguan Legation has received instructions to cease
                                discussing the boundary question after the 31st instant and it is
                                most important that the Government of the United States assume a
                                firm attitude toward both Governments.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Curtis</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>